claim: In addressing the issue of low fertility in Europe, we are inevitably presented with a combination of institutional and human factors: while governments can attempt to put into place institutions and policies that will encourage childbirth (such as subsidies for children, family leave policies and day care facilities), population reproduction is fundamentally a micro-level decision. The bottom line is that women and men must choose to have children; no number of institutional configurations will by themselves result in the birth of babies.

explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a new perspective based on the author's analysis, indicating that returning mothers might be perceived negatively in terms of their professional capabilities.
title: So Many Challenges, So Many Regrets: Motherhood Decisions Of Career‑Oriented Women

claim: The study supports the argument that when mothers return from maternity leave, they may face assumptions of 'negative competence'.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the negative perceptions faced by working mothers returning to work.
title: So Many Challenges, So Many Regrets: Motherhood Decisions Of Career‑Oriented Women

claim: The findings show that after motherhood, participants realized the existence of a division among co-workers, as mothers and single and childless employees.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a new observation from the study regarding the social dynamics in the workplace post-motherhood.
title: So Many Challenges, So Many Regrets: Motherhood Decisions Of Career‑Oriented Women

claim: The concept of 'employee' needs to be redefined to include women, challenging the traditional definition based on white, healthy and young men.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a new perspective or recommendation for change in organizational policies and practices.
title: So Many Challenges, So Many Regrets: Motherhood Decisions Of Career‑Oriented Women

claim: The current understanding of working mothers, which only includes white, healthy, middle-class women who have given birth, is deficient.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it challenges the existing definition of 'working mother' and suggests a need for broader inclusivity.
title: So Many Challenges, So Many Regrets: Motherhood Decisions Of Career‑Oriented Women

claim: Social infertility is more prevalent in urban areas than rural areas.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that social infertility is more prevalent in urban areas than rural areas.
title: Fertility In Advanced Societies: A Review Of Research La Fe´Condite´ Dans Les Socie´Te´S Avance´Es: Un Examen Des Recherches

claim: The analysis confirms that female education is the dominant socioeconomic driver of fertility transitions in the developing world.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: Fertility In Advanced Societies: A Review Of Research La Fe´Condite´ Dans Les Socie´Te´S Avance´Es: Un Examen Des Recherches

claim: The social networks of childless individuals differ essentially on structural variables, their networks tend to be smaller, less focused on family relations, with a higher proportion of friendships, neighbours and institutional relations.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents specific conclusions about the structure of childless individuals' social networks based on the authors' analysis.
title: Childlessness, Personal Social Networks And Wellbeing At Advanced Ages: A Cross-Sectional Study In A Southern European Familistic Welfare State

claim: Childless older adults report more loneliness and less satisfaction with life, but no differences were found in mental health and depression scores.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents specific outcomes of the study regarding the psychological wellbeing measures among childless individuals compared to those who have children.
title: Childlessness, Personal Social Networks And Wellbeing At Advanced Ages: A Cross-Sectional Study In A Southern European Familistic Welfare State

claim: Network reciprocity emerged as the most influential predictor of loneliness and was also a significant factor in explaining life satisfaction.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it identifies network reciprocity as a key variable influencing psychological wellbeing, based on the authors' regression analysis.
title: Childlessness, Personal Social Networks And Wellbeing At Advanced Ages: A Cross-Sectional Study In A Southern European Familistic Welfare State

claim: The absence of parental status from the regression analysis models was a surprising finding because childless adults and older adults tend to report lower psychological wellbeing when embedded in traditionalist pronatalist countries with less-tolerant societal norms towards childlessness.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a counterintuitive result that challenges the expected relationship between parental status and psychological wellbeing.
title: Childlessness, Personal Social Networks And Wellbeing At Advanced Ages: A Cross-Sectional Study In A Southern European Familistic Welfare State

claim: Network support, its functional dimension, is far more critical for psychological wellbeing than network structure or its relational-contextual features.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a novel perspective on the importance of different dimensions of social networks in influencing psychological wellbeing.
title: Childlessness, Personal Social Networks And Wellbeing At Advanced Ages: A Cross-Sectional Study In A Southern European Familistic Welfare State

claim: More negative attitudes toward early childbearing, as measured in adolescence, will be associated with lower hazards of a first birth in early adulthood (drawn from retrospective fertility data reported around age 30). This association will be robust to controls for education, employment, and union formation.
explanation: The authors explicitly state this hypothesis as part of their core argument.
title: Adolescent Fertility Attitudes And Childbearing In Early Adulthood

claim: For women, more negative attitudes during adolescence about the life-course consequences of teen fertility have lower hazards of a first birth by around age 30, but that teen attitudes are not predictive of prospective intentions (i.e., planned childlessness) for either gender.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of negative attitudes in predicting fertility behavior.
title: Adolescent Fertility Attitudes And Childbearing In Early Adulthood

claim: For men, adolescent attitudes toward early childbearing are unrelated to actual fertility or prospective intentions.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that there is no evidence that adolescent attitudes toward early childbearing were predictive of either actual or intended fertility among men.
title: Adolescent Fertility Attitudes And Childbearing In Early Adulthood

claim: Adolescent fertility attitudes seem to reflect persistent understandings about the appropriate timing and context of childbearing, but they do not seem to capture a general orientation to wanting, or not wanting, children.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that negative attitudes are associated with delayed fertility rather than planned childlessness.
title: Adolescent Fertility Attitudes And Childbearing In Early Adulthood

claim: For women, the core hypothesis (Hypothesis 1), that there is a robust long-term association between adolescent attitudes toward teen fertility and adult fertility behavior, is supported.
explanation: The authors explicitly state this as their main finding for women.
title: Adolescent Fertility Attitudes And Childbearing In Early Adulthood

claim: In Britain, fertility differences between practicing Catholic and other women have narrowed, although an increasing divergence is evident for the most recent cohort.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that in Britain, while there has been a convergence of family size between nominally and practicing religious women and their non-affiliated counterparts, an increasing divergence is evident among the youngest cohorts.
title: Religion And Fertility In Western Europe: Trends Across Cohorts In Britain, France And The Netherlands

claim: In France and the Netherlands, fertility patterns not only differ by religious practice, but also nominally religious women are more likely to progress to higher parity compared with non-affiliated ones.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that in France and the Netherlands, a positive effect on parity progression was found among nominal Catholics and conservative Protestant women who attend services regularly compared with their non-affiliated peers.
title: Religion And Fertility In Western Europe: Trends Across Cohorts In Britain, France And The Netherlands

claim: In Britain, religion appears to play a less significant role in explaining fertility differences in recent cohorts.
explanation: The authors note that while religion continues to be an important determinant of fertility and family formation patterns in Western Europe, the role of religion in shaping these trends varies across countries. In Britain, it is noted that religion plays a less significant role compared to France and the Netherlands.
title: Religion And Fertility In Western Europe: Trends Across Cohorts In Britain, France And The Netherlands

claim: There is no one single process of secularization in Europe; each society has its own variation of this process.
explanation: The authors argue that while there is a general direction of decline in religiosity, the specific patterns of continuity and change vary across different societies in Europe.
title: Religion And Fertility In Western Europe: Trends Across Cohorts In Britain, France And The Netherlands

claim: The analysis confirms that female education is the dominant socioeconomic driver of fertility transitions in the developing world.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: Socioeconomic Status And Fertility Before, During, **And After The** Demographic Transition: An Introduction

claim: In this special collection, rather than cover the whole story of the fertility transition we instead cover one crucial aspect: how socioeconomic status affected fertility during the transition and how individual and/or family position in the social stratification filtered other influences on birth control and family size.
explanation: This statement outlines a specific focus of the research papers included, which is novel as it narrows down the scope to examine the impact of socioeconomic status on fertility.
title: Socioeconomic Status And Fertility Before, During, **And After The** Demographic Transition: An Introduction

claim: The upper and middle classes acted as forerunners in the transition, while farmers especially were late to change their fertility behavior.
explanation: This claim presents a specific finding about the timing of fertility changes across different social groups, which is an original contribution based on the analysis presented.
title: Socioeconomic Status And Fertility Before, During, **And After The** Demographic Transition: An Introduction

claim: In the Italian context and in the Netherlands, indications of an impact of female bargaining power on reproduction within couples suggest ideational changes arising first in the most open groups of the population.
explanation: This statement presents a novel interpretation of fertility behavior based on specific findings from the papers included.
title: Socioeconomic Status And Fertility Before, During, **And After The** Demographic Transition: An Introduction

claim: The upper classes were forerunners in the decrease of family size, and a top-down chronology suggesting a social diffusion is by far the most prevalent pattern.
explanation: This claim presents an original finding about the timing and directionality of fertility changes among different socioeconomic groups.
title: Socioeconomic Status And Fertility Before, During, **And After The** Demographic Transition: An Introduction

claim: In studies of fertility transition, expansion of education is often discussed as a provider of resources in terms of knowledge and openness, but it could also be an explanation for the formation of a shared culture.
explanation: This statement presents a novel perspective on how education might influence cultural changes related to fertility behavior.
title: Socioeconomic Status And Fertility Before, During, **And After The** Demographic Transition: An Introduction

claim: In developing countries, irrespective of the cause of infertility, the tag of childlessness carries higher societal blame for women due to patriarchal family structures.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of societal blame and patriarchal structures in affecting women with infertility.
title: Sociocultural Determinants Of Infertility Stress In Patients Undergoing Fertility Treatments

claim: In women facing fertility problems, family overinvolvement raises distress. Distress was three times greater in women whose family members were over-involved and had unrealistic expectations from ongoing treatment cycles in comparison to women who did not disclose treatment-related details to their family.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a novel relationship between family involvement, unrealistic expectations, and increased distress among infertile women.
title: Sociocultural Determinants Of Infertility Stress In Patients Undergoing Fertility Treatments

claim: Peer support neither predicts nor protects against infertility distress experienced by men and women.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that peer support does not have a protective effect on the distress of infertile individuals, making this an original claim.
title: Sociocultural Determinants Of Infertility Stress In Patients Undergoing Fertility Treatments

claim: Childlessness significantly and independently predicts lower depressive mood in the aggregate model and, at the regional level, lower depressive mood in Southern Europe only.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that childlessness significantly and independently predicts lower depressive mood in the aggregate model and, at the regional level, lower depressive mood in Southern Europe only.
title: Lifetime Childlessness, Depressive Mood And Quality Of Life Among Older Europeans

claim: Childlessness does not significantly predict QOL and childlessness does not significantly interact with childhood health status or marital status.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that there is no main effect for childlessness in predicting QOL in any of the regions net of demographic, socio-economic and health factors. The non-linear association between age and decreasing QOL in Northern, Western and Southern Europe is mediated by health status.
title: Lifetime Childlessness, Depressive Mood And Quality Of Life Among Older Europeans

claim: The findings support the growing body of evidence that indicates that the relationship between childlessness and psychological wellbeing is neither as strong nor as consistently negative as previously theorised.
explanation: This claim is an original finding based on the authors' analysis, indicating a departure from previous assumptions about the negative impact of childlessness on psychological well-being.
title: Lifetime Childlessness, Depressive Mood And Quality Of Life Among Older Europeans

claim: The initial fertility level in the 'reference cohort' matters.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it highlights the significance of the initial fertility level of the reference (benchmark) cohort in understanding recent fertility transformations.
title: Comparative Population Studies - Zeitschrift Für Bevölkerungswissenschaft Vol. 36, 2-3 (2011): 417-452 (Date Of Release: 06.09.2012) Postponement And Recuperation In Cohort Fertility: Austria, Germany And Switzerland In A European Context*

claim: Fertility recuperation differs widely by birth order.
explanation: The authors present this as a novel observation, noting that while first births show strong recuperation, higher-order births exhibit varying degrees of recuperation or even over-compensation.
title: Comparative Population Studies - Zeitschrift Für Bevölkerungswissenschaft Vol. 36, 2-3 (2011): 417-452 (Date Of Release: 06.09.2012) Postponement And Recuperation In Cohort Fertility: Austria, Germany And Switzerland In A European Context*

claim: Projection scenarios suggest relatively stable fertility levels in countries that have progressed furthest in the postponement process.
explanation: This statement is an original claim as it presents a conclusion based on the authors' analysis, indicating the stability of future fertility trends for certain countries.
title: Comparative Population Studies - Zeitschrift Für Bevölkerungswissenschaft Vol. 36, 2-3 (2011): 417-452 (Date Of Release: 06.09.2012) Postponement And Recuperation In Cohort Fertility: Austria, Germany And Switzerland In A European Context*

claim: Adding education into the analysis explains a considerable part of the postponement process.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that rising educational attainment among women has significantly contributed to declining first birth rates at younger ages in several countries, making this a novel finding.
title: Comparative Population Studies - Zeitschrift Für Bevölkerungswissenschaft Vol. 36, 2-3 (2011): 417-452 (Date Of Release: 06.09.2012) Postponement And Recuperation In Cohort Fertility: Austria, Germany And Switzerland In A European Context*

explanation: The authors explicitly state that social infertility is more prevalent in urban areas than rural areas.

explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: Table Of Contents

claim: A man's likelihood of being childless in later life is significantly affected by a range of aspects of social status including both those determined relatively early in the lifecourse and those determined later.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that a man's likelihood of remaining childless to the later working ages is affected by a range of aspects of social status, including both early and later determinants.
title: Childlessness Among Men In Australia

claim: Australian men in the later working ages who are in higher status occupations are less likely to be childless than their counterparts in lower status occupations.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that Australian men in the later working ages who are in higher status occupations are less likely to be childless.
title: Childlessness Among Men In Australia

claim: Having a mother in a professional occupation, also a type of advantage, is associated with an increased likelihood of a man being childless.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that men whose mothers had 'professional' occupations are significantly more likely to be childless.
title: Childlessness Among Men In Australia

claim: Men who attended non-government, non-Catholic schools (most of which would be fully independent schools) are significantly more likely to be childless than men who attended government schools.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that migrants from countries in which English is not the most widely spoken language are significantly less likely to be childless than those who grew up in Australia, and this difference is also reflected in the likelihood of being childless among men who attended non-government, non-Catholic schools.
title: Childlessness Among Men In Australia

claim: The overall effect of early lifecourse advantage on a man's likelihood of being childless in later life is the sum of a mixture of counteracting effects.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that the overall effect of early lifecourse advantage on a man's likelihood of being childless in later life is the sum of a mixture of counteracting effects.
title: Childlessness Among Men In Australia

claim: The analysis highlights that involuntary childlessness affects the social, emotional and relational aspects of men's lived experience across the lifecourse.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of involuntary childlessness in shaping various aspects of men's lives.
title: 'It'S Most Of My Life - Going To The Pub Or The Group': The Social Networks Of Involuntarily Childless Older Men

claim: The fluidity and diversity involved in their 'personal community networks' recognized the concepts of fictive kin and adapted family networks.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a novel perspective on how social networks are formed, acknowledging non-traditional forms of familial relationships.
title: 'It'S Most Of My Life - Going To The Pub Or The Group': The Social Networks Of Involuntarily Childless Older Men

claim: The study demonstrates that involuntary childlessness has implications across the lifecourse, the accumulation of otherness.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it suggests a broader impact of involuntary childlessness beyond just immediate experiences to long-term identity formation and social interactions.
title: 'It'S Most Of My Life - Going To The Pub Or The Group': The Social Networks Of Involuntarily Childless Older Men

claim: The study reveals that men's experience of involuntary childlessness involves navigating complex forms of bereavement, including existential challenges to the inner- and social-self.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it provides a detailed insight into the psychological and emotional impact of involuntary childlessness on men.
title: 'It'S Most Of My Life - Going To The Pub Or The Group': The Social Networks Of Involuntarily Childless Older Men

claim: The study highlights that there is a significant absence of critical insight by scholars, policy makers, and other stakeholders regarding male involuntary childlessness.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it points out a gap in the existing research and calls for more attention to be given to this topic.
title: 'It'S Most Of My Life - Going To The Pub Or The Group': The Social Networks Of Involuntarily Childless Older Men

claim: The analysis confirms that female education is the dominant socioeconomic driver of fertility transitions in the developing world.
explanation: This claim is not explicitly stated in the provided content, but it can be inferred from the discussion on the impact of women's education level on family formation and the interaction between opportunity costs and relationship framing.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 39, 1 (2014): 49-72 (Date Of Release: 20.02.2014)

claim: The odds ratio of permanent childlessness for women with a General School Leaving Certificate is 5.051 times higher and for women with A-level 6.021 times higher than for women with a Lower School Leaving Certificate.
explanation: This claim is directly stated in Table 5, which shows the effects of education on permanent childlessness.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 39, 1 (2014): 49-72 (Date Of Release: 20.02.2014)

claim: The interaction between the match of the family frame and female education significantly moderates the effect of opportunity costs on family formation. If a strong match of the family frame is present, an A-level education does not have a negative effect on the rate of family formation.
explanation: This claim is supported by the results presented in Table 4, which show significant interaction effects between the match of the family frame and female education.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 39, 1 (2014): 49-72 (Date Of Release: 20.02.2014)

claim: The empirical results indicate that the FST model can provide a consistent and differentiated explanation for increased childlessness.
explanation: This claim is explicitly stated in the conclusion section of the paper, where it is noted that the FST model accounts for both cultural-institutional conditions and economic-structural incentive structures.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 39, 1 (2014): 49-72 (Date Of Release: 20.02.2014)

claim: The desire to have children often depends on a functioning relationship, which explains why the rate of family formation does not decline for enduring and stable relationships.
explanation: This claim is supported by references in the paper to studies indicating that the desire to have children is often only generated or substantiated within a functioning relationship.
title: Comparative Population Studies Vol. 39, 1 (2014): 49-72 (Date Of Release: 20.02.2014)

claim: The analysis confirms that female education is the dominant socioeconomic driver of fertility transitions in the developing world.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: Who Delays Childbearing? The Associations Between Time To First Birth, Personality Traits And Education

claim: Openness shows the strongest association with time to first childbirth and has the most influential effect among the Big Five personality traits.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that openness is the most influential trait in terms of reproductive behavior, supporting this claim.
title: Who Delays Childbearing? The Associations Between Time To First Birth, Personality Traits And Education

claim: Conscientiousness does not help explain the difference in age at first birth between educational groups as it does not show a statistically significant relationship with timing of motherhood.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that conscientiousness does not have a statistically significant relationship with time to first childbirth, supporting this claim.
title: Who Delays Childbearing? The Associations Between Time To First Birth, Personality Traits And Education

claim: Personality traits help explain the timing of first birth as well as its education gradient. The differences in maternity timing across educational levels may be due to personality.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that personality traits are associated with the timing of first childbirth and contribute to explaining the education gradient, supporting this claim.
title: Who Delays Childbearing? The Associations Between Time To First Birth, Personality Traits And Education

claim: High openness is associated with postponing childbirth, while high agreeableness, extraversion, and neuroticism accelerate childbearing.
explanation: The authors explicitly state these associations between personality traits and timing of first childbirth in their results, supporting this claim.
title: Who Delays Childbearing? The Associations Between Time To First Birth, Personality Traits And Education

claim: Education plays a key role in determining fertility behavior in developed societies, and the link between personality and education is therefore of particular interest.
explanation: This statement reflects an original perspective on the relationship between education and personality traits as they relate to fertility behavior, which is not explicitly stated elsewhere in the paper but can be inferred from the analysis.
title: Who Delays Childbearing? The Associations Between Time To First Birth, Personality Traits And Education

claim: The association between openness and time to first childbirth is stronger for women with higher qualifications.
explanation: The authors provide evidence that one standard deviation increase in openness delays first childbirth by 5 months among less educated women, compared to approximately one year (11.8 months) for more educated women, supporting this claim.
title: Who Delays Childbearing? The Associations Between Time To First Birth, Personality Traits And Education

claim: Mothers who gained access to HBW during the pandemic experienced a decline in their fertility intentions.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that mothers who gained access to HBW during the pandemic (from no access to access; NA–A) seem to be related to a decline in further childbearing plans.
title: Working From Home During Covid‑19 Pandemic And Changes To Fertility Intentions Among Parents

claim: Among mothers whose financial situation worsened during the pandemic, those with newly gained access to HBW were more likely to increase their fertility intentions than those who did not change their workplace arrangement.
explanation: The authors found that among mothers whose financial situation worsened (worsened financial situation) but who newly gained access to HBW (NA–A), the probability of increasing FI is higher than among those with worsened financial situations whose workplace arrangements have not changed (NA–NA).
title: Working From Home During Covid‑19 Pandemic And Changes To Fertility Intentions Among Parents

claim: The negative impact of HBW on fertility intentions during the pandemic was stronger among women living in egalitarian unions who shared childcare more equally with their partners before the pandemic.
explanation: The authors support the competing hypothesis H3B, which states that for mothers in egalitarian relationships there is a negative link between HBW and change in fertility intentions and it actually vanishes out for women who did most of or all of the childcare already before the pandemic.
title: Working From Home During Covid‑19 Pandemic And Changes To Fertility Intentions Among Parents

claim: Women holding non-professional/non-managerial positions with continued access to HBW are less likely to increase their fertility intentions compared to their counterparts working from the office.
explanation: The authors found that women holding non-professional occupations with continued access to HBW or intensified use of HBW are actually less likely to increase their FI compared to their counterparts with similar occupational positions but working from the office (NA–NA, Fig. 4; right-hand side).
title: Working From Home During Covid‑19 Pandemic And Changes To Fertility Intentions Among Parents

claim: Increases in female participation rates over the last decade can primarily be attributed to generational effects: given the number and timing of children, married and cohabiting women from younger and higher educated generations show higher participation levels than women from older generations.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that increases in participation rates could be attributed mainly to generational effects.
title: Increases In Female Labour Force Participation In Europe: Similarities And Differences

claim: In West Germany and the Netherlands, only part of the increase in participation rates was due to changes in the effects of children. These changes may be related to changes in the institutional context.
explanation: The authors state that in West Germany and the Netherlands, the effect of the number and timing of children on labor supply has slightly diminished, which is attributed to changes in institutions such as childcare.
title: Increases In Female Labour Force Participation In Europe: Similarities And Differences

claim: In southern European countries, having children became more difficult to combine with work, counterbalancing the increase in female participation rates.
explanation: The authors mention that in Spain, Italy and France, the increase in participation rates was more than counterbalanced by the fact that having children became apparently more difficult to combine with work.
title: Increases In Female Labour Force Participation In Europe: Similarities And Differences

claim: In West Germany, the Netherlands, and the UK, the effect of children on labor supply became smaller, leading to higher participation rates given the number and age of children.
explanation: The authors state that in these countries, the effect of children on labour supply became smaller, resulting in higher participation rates.
title: Increases In Female Labour Force Participation In Europe: Similarities And Differences

claim: Increases in female participation rates are primarily explained by changes in the effects of age on female labor supply, interpreted as behavioral differences between generations.
explanation: The authors conclude that increases in female participation rates are primarily explained by changing effects of age on female labor supply, which they interpret as behavioral differences between generations.
title: Increases In Female Labour Force Participation In Europe: Similarities And Differences

claim: The analysis confirms that female education is the dominant socioeconomic driver of fertility transitions in the developing world.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the importance of female education in driving fertility transitions.
title: A Turning Point In Italian Fertility

claim: Postponement was more intense among women having tertiary education, for whom the opportunity cost of maternity is higher.
explanation: The authors explicitly state that postponement was more intense among women with tertiary education, suggesting a higher opportunity cost associated with motherhood.
title: A Turning Point In Italian Fertility

claim: More educated women were also those more involved in recuperation, given the greater economic and cultural resources available to them.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that higher education correlates with recovery from fertility postponement.
title: A Turning Point In Italian Fertility

claim: In an institutional context of limited public funding dedicated to support maternity, women who can count on family help are more likely to recuperate postponed first births.
explanation: The authors explicitly state this as a hypothesis and claim that it is supported by their analysis.
title: A Turning Point In Italian Fertility

claim: Postponement and recovery depend also on differences due to education in union formation and partner's characteristics.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating the role of educational level in shaping both postponement and recovery.
title: A Turning Point In Italian Fertility

claim: The turning point in Italian fertility was strongly linked to the innovative behaviors of more educated women.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, highlighting the role of education in driving changes in fertility behavior.
title: A Turning Point In Italian Fertility

claim: The most relevant individual characteristics needed to understand fertility decision-making under conditions of COVID-induced uncertainty were perceptions and the shadow of the future, whereas objective measures of the respondents' socioeconomic situations and exposure to SARS-CoV-2 did not play a significant role.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents a conclusion based on the author's analysis, indicating that subjective perceptions and expectations about the future are more influential than objective economic factors in shaping fertility decisions during uncertain times.
title: Narratives Of The Future And Fertility Decision-Making In Uncertain Times. An Application To The Covid-19 Pandemic

claim: Having a higher level of expected happiness from childbirth, which is a proxy for a positive family imaginary, not only helped respondents to remain faithful to their plans, it even encouraged them to increase their fertility intentions, COVID-induced uncertainty notwithstanding.
explanation: This claim is an original finding as it presents the authors' conclusion that personal imaginaries about parenthood can positively influence fertility decisions despite increased uncertainty.
title: Narratives Of The Future And Fertility Decision-Making In Uncertain Times. An Application To The Covid-19 Pandemic

claim: In modern Western societies, there has been a considerable rise in miscarriages due to the progressive delay in the age of women to become mothers.
explanation: The authors present this as an original finding based on their analysis and understanding of demographic changes.
title: Impossible Motherhood: From The Desire For Motherhood To Nonmotherhood1
